node.text: Thanks to your generous contributions, this year bison returned to land they hadn’t occupied since 1877! Bison now have an additional 22,000 acres of protected land in Badlands National Park.

8 million metric tons of plastic waste are dumped into the ocean every year, putting millions of species and people at risk. Today you can protect oceans and all of nature from plastic pollution, climate change, and other threats. Donate now by following the link in our bio.

Thanks to WWF’s Irene Magafan for sharing this post with us! | Here I am in the field in Tsavo East National Park, Kenya where I found myself 6 feet from a gorgeous African elephant who was roaming the plains. During this trip, I was able to observe many animals in their natural habitat, learn about their plight and populations and take this knowledge back with me to help tell the story of our work. Being around these magnificent beings has only made me more driven and motivated to work on behalf of wildlife and wild places to help keep their numbers up, preserve the populations that exist and help maintain healthy ecosystems. I’m thankful for our supporters. Without them, we simply could not do the tireless and inspiring work we do. Thank you for believing in our planet and all of the work that needs to continue to keep our natural world and communities thriving.

Some good news for conservation! Mountain gorilla numbers rise in a Central African protected forest. A recent survey revealed the largest number of mountain gorillas ever recorded in a large swathe of protected forest in Uganda and the Democratic Republic of the Congo. WWF and partners counted 459 individuals, up from an estimated 400 in 2011, in the 83,840-acre Bwindi-Sarambwe ecosystem that runs from Bwindi Impenetrable National Park, Uganda, through the Sarambwe Nature Reserve, Democratic Republic of the Congo. “It’s remarkable to see that the positive trend for mountain gorillas continues since it was once thought the species might be extinct by the end of the 20th century. Effective long-term conservation efforts have helped both the Virunga and Bwindi populations increase and sustaining this incredible result will be contingent on sustaining those efforts.” - Bas Huijbregts, African species director at WWF.

Video courtesy of WWF’s Monica Echeverria | Last week I had the amazing experience of visiting the Monarch Butterfly Biosphere Reserve in Mexico. Every year, at the end of the Summer, these butterflies migrate for nearly 2,800 miles from the United States and Canada to hibernate in this forest in central Mexico, where they find the right weather conditions to shelter during the Winter 
Video cortesía de Mónica Echeverría, WWF-US | La semana pasada tuve la oportunidad de visitar la Reserva de la Biosfera de la Mariposa Monarca, en México. Cada año, al final del verano, estas mariposas migran unas 2,800 millas desde Estados Unidos y Canadá para hibernar en este bosque ubicado en el centro de México, donde encuentran las condiciones climáticas adecuadas para refugiarse durante el invierno.

Today, conservation organizations released over 4.5 million camera trap records as a part of @wildlifeinsights, a groundbreaking cloud platform that provides vital, near real-time information about the wildlife populations across the globe. This new effort could greatly expand our knowledge of wildlife, helping us to better anticipate threats, understand where and why wildlife populations are changing, and take action to protect wildlife. Want to learn more? Check out the link in our bio.

We are thrilled to announce that world-famous DJ, @Arminvanbuuren has joined WWF as a Global Oceans Ambassador to motivate millions of people to join the movement to keep plastic waste out of our oceans. 
Armin says: “In between tours, I visited several WWF projects on Bali. There I could see with my own eyes how beautiful animals like turtles are affected by plastic pollution. These experiences opened my eyes and made me realize how much aid is needed. For years, I have been bringing people together through music. That’s my way of making the world a little better. Besides being a DJ and producer, I am also a father and I want to give my kids the world they deserve, a world that not only they can appreciate, but one that can be enjoyed by many generations to come. The WWF’s inspiring message of nature conservation appeals to me as a father, a person and a public figure. I’m proud to announce we are joining forces and that I can call myself a Global Oceans Ambassador.”

At #COP25 large polluters resisted efforts to keep global warming below 1.5°C. The role the US Administration played in the negotiations at COP25 is at odds and out of touch with a clear majority of Americans, scientific facts and the needs of a world facing a climate crisis. At a time when the federal government is turning its back on the global effort to address climate change, we need all parts of the US government and American society to move in unison toward ambitious climate action if we are going to deliver a stable future for life on Earth.

Did you know there are nearly 20,000 known bee species in the world? 🐝 4,000 of them are native to the United States and Canada. Bees are critical to healthy ecosystems and are experiencing steep population decline. To bring awareness to this issue, WWF and @Minecraft have teamed up, and starting today buzzy bees are now available in the world-building game of Minecraft. Click the link in our bio to learn how Minecraft is supporting WWF’s global conservation work.

Have you heard of climate overshoot? It’s the period of time in which warming is increasing past 1.5°C (2.7° F) and then cools back down. Climate models predict that there may be years if not decades of higher global temperatures before stabilizing at 1.5°C. Long periods of higher global temperatures could result in many different damaging outcomes for a wide variety of ecosystems, including increased coastal flooding and forced human migration, greater devastation and frequency of forest fires, and loss of biodiversity. The conversion of new land for agricultural use may put additional stress on animal habitats, and when temperatures level off and cool, we may see animals migrating in search of habitats that no longer exist. We must think beyond end-of-the-century warming at 1.5°C and place additional focus on how peak warming could impact people and nature. WWF is building momentum for a low-carbon economy and pushing to end illegal logging and restore forests for long lasting carbon capture. #COP25
Dolphins and porpoises may look alike, but they’re different. How can you tell them apart? Here’s a clue: dolphins have longer snouts and bigger mouths than porpoises.

A tiger stalks through the forest in Nepal’s Bardia National Park. Photographer Emmanuel Rondeau spent weeks trying to capture this image using a camera trap. His patience paid off! This wild tiger eventually crossed his camera’s path, leading to this stunning photo. Camera traps are triggered to snap photos when an animal crosses an infrared beam. Want to get more behind-the-scenes information? Click the link in our bio. #tigers

"We really need to prepare ourselves, to increase ambition, and make some moves on climate change." - WWF's Ryan Finnegan. Yesterday people took to the streets of Madrid to call on the countries at the 25th Conference of Parties to increase their efforts to halt the worst impacts of a changing climate. Mobilizations like this are happening all over the world in order to bring attention to the #climatecrisis, demanding stronger action in the fight against climate change. #COP25

Less than 200 of Malaysia's tigers are now estimated to be left in the wild. What’s the greatest threat to their survival? Poaching. This activity has grown in recent years due to an influx of Indochinese poachers, who snare heavily and can wipe out entire populations of large animals if left unchecked. We are calling for the establishment of a National Tiger Conservation Committee and spearheading multiple other tiger conservation initiatives. Click the link in our bio to learn more about Malaysia's tigers and what you can do to help.

Exciting news for jaguars on #InternationalJaguarDay! A flourishing population of jaguars was revealed on a recent mission on an Amazonian island off the coast of Brazil. The mission identified at least 20 jaguars, three of which were collared by scientists in order to better understand the behavior of one of the Amazon's most iconic species.
